---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Financial Reporting & Analytics Dashboard | All Webbed Labs",
  metaDescription: "How we helped a Sydney accounting firm cut board pack preparation from 2-3 days per client to a single automated run, saving 14 hours per accountant per month and improving client NPS by 28 points.",

  industry: "Financial Services",
  tags: ["Accounting Automation", "API Integrations", "Data Visualisation", "Report Generation", "Cloud Infrastructure"],

  title: "Financial Reporting & Analytics Dashboard",
  summary: "A Sydney accounting firm was spending the first two weeks of every month buried in spreadsheets — manually pulling client financials from Xero, MYOB, and QuickBooks and reassembling them into PowerPoint board packs. We built an automated multi-platform reporting dashboard that delivered polished, consistent reports in minutes, not days.",

  heroImageDescription: "Multi-panel financial dashboard showing P&L trends, cash flow charts, and automated board pack generation interface across Xero, MYOB, and QuickBooks data sources",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Pinnacle Advisory Group is a mid-sized accounting and business advisory firm based in Sydney's CBD, serving 180 SME clients across industries including hospitality, professional services, and trade businesses. The firm employs 28 staff across accounting, advisory, and administration roles, with four partners who collectively manage client relationships and lead complex engagements.",
  clientSize: "28 staff, 180 SME clients",
  clientLocation: "Sydney, NSW",

  pullQuote: "We used to joke that the first two weeks of every month belonged to the clients' books, not to the clients themselves. Now our partners are actually having strategic conversations instead of chasing formula errors in Excel.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "David Chau",
  pullQuoteRole: "Managing Partner, Pinnacle Advisory Group",

  challenge: [
    "Every month without fail, the cycle started the same way. Accountants would log into each client's accounting platform — Xero for most, MYOB for a handful of the longer-standing clients, and QuickBooks for a couple of clients who'd migrated from the US — and begin the laborious process of exporting data. Profit and loss reports in one tab, balance sheets in another, cash flow statements copied across, and bank reconciliation summaries pasted in by hand. For 180 clients, this was not a minor inconvenience. It was a structural drain on the firm.",
    "The formatting inconsistency was a particular source of frustration. Different accountants had developed their own Excel templates over time, meaning a client who changed account managers halfway through the year would receive a completely different-looking report. Partners spent hours before sending a pack reviewing formatting rather than reviewing the financials themselves. Board packs for clients with complex group structures could take the better part of three days to assemble from scratch.",
    "The timing problem compounded everything. Because the manual process took so long, board packs routinely arrived after the board meetings they were supposed to inform. The firm's benchmark was delivery within five business days of month end, but the reality was an average of eight days late — meaning many clients were reviewing last month's numbers a full three weeks after the period had closed. For owner-operators making decisions about payroll, capex, and cash reserves, stale data at that lag was a genuine operational problem.",
    "Partners were losing billable hours to formatting work that any competent junior could do — except that with 28 staff serving 180 clients, there was no slack in the system to absorb that kind of delegation. The firm had explored off-the-shelf reporting platforms, but the multi-platform reality (Xero, MYOB, and QuickBooks under the same roof) meant none of the purpose-built tools covered their full client base without expensive per-seat licensing that would have wiped out the efficiency gains. The partners came to us looking for something built around their actual workflow."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The partners at Pinnacle had spoken to two other software consultancies before reaching us. Both had proposed building a custom connector for each accounting platform but had quoted the work as three separate projects with separate timelines — meaning the MYOB clients would wait six months longer than the Xero clients to see any benefit. That sequenced approach didn't reflect the reality that the pain was firm-wide from day one.",
    "What convinced the partners to work with us was the discovery phase. We spent two days in their offices during month-end, watching accountants work in real time — not just interviewing them about the process but seeing where they actually lost time. We mapped the exact data fields they pulled from each platform, the manual adjustments they made for client-specific KPIs, and the points in the workflow where errors were most likely to creep in. That level of specificity meant our proposal matched what they actually needed, not a generic automation platform with a reporting module bolted on."
  ],

  approach: [
    "We started with a data audit across the three accounting platforms. The Xero API is well-documented and relatively consistent; MYOB's AccountRight API has some idiosyncrasies around how it handles multi-currency accounts; QuickBooks Online's API requires careful handling of report-level endpoints versus entity-level data. Understanding the quirks of each platform before writing a line of production code saved us from building a normalisation layer that would have been constantly patching platform-specific edge cases.",
    "From the data audit, we designed a canonical financial data model — a consistent internal representation that every report template would read from, regardless of the source platform. This was the architectural decision that made everything else possible. Whether a client was on Xero or MYOB, the dashboard would receive the same structured data objects: a P&L with standardised account categories, a balance sheet with mapped line items, and a cash flow statement with consistent period-over-period comparisons.",
    "We ran a co-design session with three of Pinnacle's accountants to define the report templates. Rather than translating their existing PowerPoint layouts pixel-for-pixel, we used this as an opportunity to rethink what a board pack actually needed to communicate. The result was a set of modular report sections — executive summary, P&L trend, cash position, accounts receivable ageing, and a configurable KPI panel — that could be assembled into a full pack with a single click or turned into standalone snapshots for clients who only needed a cash flow update.",
    "The technology decision on PDF generation took some deliberation. We evaluated several approaches before landing on Puppeteer headless Chrome rendering. The rationale was straightforward: the firm's clients expected PDF board packs that looked like designed documents, not database exports. By rendering the reports as web pages first — using React and Chart.js for the visualisation layer — and then capturing them to PDF, we got full typographic control, pixel-perfect chart rendering, and the ability to preview reports in-browser before generating the PDF. The browser-first approach also meant the online dashboard and the PDF outputs were always visually consistent."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The core of the platform is a data synchronisation service that runs nightly and on-demand. When an accountant triggers a report, the system authenticates with the client's accounting platform via OAuth, pulls the relevant financial data for the selected period, and maps it into the canonical data model. For clients on Xero, this happens in under 30 seconds. MYOB's API is somewhat slower — typically 60 to 90 seconds for a full month sync — so we queue those requests and notify the accountant when data is ready rather than making them wait at the screen.",
    "The dashboard itself gives accountants a per-client view with configurable KPI tiles, interactive charts built in Chart.js, and a report builder panel on the right. Building a board pack is a matter of selecting the period, choosing which sections to include, reviewing the automated commentary draft (which we generate by comparing current-period figures against prior period and prior year), and clicking Generate. The PDF is produced in the background, emailed directly to the client's nominated board recipients, and archived in the client's file with a delivery timestamp.",
    "We built client-specific customisation into the data model from the start. Some of Pinnacle's hospitality clients wanted covers-per-day and labour-cost-as-a-percentage-of-revenue tracked as headline KPIs alongside standard P&L lines. Professional services clients needed work-in-progress balances and realisation rates. Rather than building these as rigid modules, we designed a custom metrics engine that lets accountants define derived metrics using a simple formula builder — a named metric, a source field or fields from the canonical model, and a calculation type. These custom KPIs are then available in any report section.",
    "User access and permissions were given careful thought given that the platform would hold financial data for 180 businesses. Each client's data is partitioned at the database level, not just filtered at the application level. Accountants are assigned to specific clients by the firm admin, and can only access data for clients on their list. Partners have a firm-wide view but cannot export raw data in bulk — only individual client reports through the standard workflow. All data in transit uses TLS 1.3; data at rest in PostgreSQL is encrypted using AWS RDS encryption.",
    "The automated commentary feature deserves its own mention because it was the piece the partners were most sceptical about and ended up most pleased with. The commentary engine compares key line items against prior period and generates plain-English observations: 'Revenue increased 12% on prior month, primarily driven by a $34K increase in consulting fees.' It doesn't attempt to explain causation — that's the accountant's job — but it drafts the factual observations so that accountants start from something, rather than from a blank text field. In practice, most accountants edit perhaps 30% of the generated commentary before sending."
  ],

  implementation: [
    "We used an agile delivery cadence with two-week sprints, but the real discipline came from keeping the first sprint deliberately narrow. Sprint one delivered a working Xero integration with a single report template for a single pilot client. Four of Pinnacle's accountants reviewed it on day fifteen and gave us two hours of detailed feedback before we wrote another line of code. The scope adjustments from that session — primarily around how the prior-year comparison was displayed and the handling of GST-inclusive versus exclusive line items — would have been expensive to change later if we'd tried to build the full platform before showing it to real users.",
    "MYOB and QuickBooks integrations followed in sprints two and three, with the canonical data model doing the heavy lifting of keeping the application layer consistent. The custom metrics engine was built in sprint four after we'd confirmed that the core reporting workflow was stable. PDF generation and the email delivery system came in sprint five, which put a fully functional end-to-end workflow in front of the whole firm for user acceptance testing three months into the project.",
    "Onboarding 180 clients to the platform was handled through a migration sprint rather than a big-bang cutover. We built a bulk OAuth connection flow that let accountants authorise platform access for multiple clients in a single session, with a progress dashboard showing connection status per client. The full client base was connected within four weeks of launch. We ran parallel reporting for the first two months — automated reports alongside the old manual process — so the team could verify accuracy before decommissioning the spreadsheet workflow entirely."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The MYOB API's handling of comparative balance sheet data caught us late in testing. MYOB's AccountRight API returns comparative period data differently depending on whether the client's financial year matches the calendar year, and a handful of Pinnacle's clients had non-standard year-ends. We'd tested primarily against standard year-end configurations and only discovered the edge case during UAT. The fix was not complex, but it added a sprint to the MYOB stream. The lesson: test against the messiest real-world client data from sprint one, not from sprint three.",
    "We underestimated the appetite for the in-browser dashboard relative to the PDF output. We'd scoped the browser interface primarily as a report-review step before PDF generation, but accountants quickly started using it as a live client portal — keeping it open during client calls to answer questions on the spot. This was a genuinely positive surprise, but it prompted a round of UX work in the post-launch period to improve the interactive chart features and add a notes field that accountants could use to annotate figures during calls. The lesson: build the web interface as if it will be used independently, not as a stepping stone.",
    "Change management at the firm level mattered more than we'd anticipated. Two of the firm's more experienced accountants were resistant to the automated commentary feature, viewing it as a threat to a skill they'd spent years developing. We responded by making the commentary completely optional — easily toggled off per client — and by positioning it as a first-draft tool rather than a replacement for accountant judgement. Both accountants became comfortable with the feature within a month once they saw it as saving them 20 minutes of drafting rather than replacing their expertise."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Six months after launch, Pinnacle approached us to extend the platform with a client-facing portal — a read-only view that allows business owners to log in and see their own financial dashboards between formal reporting cycles. We built this as a separate subdomain with a simplified view of the key metrics, designed specifically for non-accountants: larger numbers, more contextual benchmarks, less accounting terminology. The portal is now offered as a premium tier of the firm's advisory service.",
    "The partner group is also exploring using the platform's aggregated (anonymised) data to generate industry benchmarks for their hospitality and professional services client cohorts — giving each client a sense of how their margins and cash conversion compare to similar businesses. We've scoped this as a future phase, with careful attention to data privacy obligations under the Privacy Act 1988 and the firm's own confidentiality obligations to clients."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "The numbers below came from a combination of time-tracking data the firm had kept internally and a client satisfaction survey run six months post-launch. The firm was careful to attribute results conservatively — the NPS improvement, for example, reflects the full advisory relationship, not just the reporting tool. That said, the time savings are direct and measurable: the manual reporting workflow is gone, and the hours it consumed are now visible in the timesheet system as billable advisory work.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "14hrs", label: "Saved per accountant per month", context: "Time previously spent on manual data extraction and formatting" },
    { value: "9 days", label: "Earlier delivery of board packs", context: "From average 8 days late to 1 day early" },
    { value: "180", label: "Clients on platform", context: "Full client base connected within 4 months of launch" },
    { value: "+31%", label: "Partner time on value-added work", context: "Billable hours shifted from formatting to advisory" },
    { value: "+28pts", label: "Client satisfaction NPS improvement", context: "Measured 6 months post-launch" },
    { value: "Zero", label: "Formatting errors in delivered reports", context: "Compared to recurring errors in the prior manual process" }
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Component-based UI for the dashboard and report builder, with good charting library support" },
    { name: "Python", reason: "Data ingestion and normalisation layer, API clients for Xero, MYOB, and QuickBooks" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Primary data store with client-level data partitioning and RDS encryption at rest" },
    { name: "Xero API", reason: "OAuth 2.0 integration for the majority of the client base" },
    { name: "MYOB AccountRight API", reason: "Integration for legacy MYOB clients with custom handling for non-standard year-ends" },
    { name: "QuickBooks Online API", reason: "Integration for clients migrating from or operating across international entities" },
    { name: "Chart.js", reason: "Interactive financial charts in the browser dashboard, consistent with PDF output" },
    { name: "Puppeteer", reason: "Headless Chrome PDF generation from React-rendered report templates" },
    { name: "AWS (RDS, S3, Lambda)", reason: "Managed database, report archive storage, and serverless sync jobs" },
    { name: "Node.js (Express)", reason: "API gateway layer handling authentication, authorisation, and request routing" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Expense Management & Approval Workflow",
      href: "/case-studies/expense-management-approval-workflow",
      industry: "Financial Services",
      summary: "Replaced paper expense forms and manual ERP entry for a Brisbane construction company, cutting approval cycles from 21 days to 3.2 days and eliminating receipt loss."
    },
    {
      title: "Loan Application & Assessment Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/loan-application-assessment-platform",
      industry: "Financial Services",
      summary: "Transformed a paper-and-fax loan application process for a Melbourne non-bank lender, reducing assessment time from 5 days to 4 hours average."
    },
    {
      title: "Document Management & Approval Workflow",
      href: "/case-studies/document-management-approval-workflow",
      industry: "Professional Services",
      summary: "Built a structured document lifecycle system with version control, role-based approvals, and audit trail for a multi-site professional services firm."
    }
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: "Custom Software Development", href: "/services/custom-software-development" },
    { title: "API Integration & Automation", href: "/services/api-integration-automation" },
    { title: "Data & Analytics", href: "/services/data-analytics" },
    { title: "Cloud Infrastructure", href: "/services/cloud-infrastructure" }
  ]
};
